<span id="vi.xxxi-p14"></span> The appointment of elders in every church
(which the apostles visited on this journey) is made by Paul and
Barnabas. Meyer supposes that the apostles only superintended the
popular choice by the church itself. The word employed (<span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p14.1"></span>χειροτονέω</span>),
meaning to stretch forth the hand, as in voting would seem especially
appropriate to the idea of a popular election, but the participle here
employed (<span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p14.2"></span>χειροτονήσαντες</span>) has not *the church*
but Paul and Barnabas for its subject. It seems necessary, therefore, to
take it in the general and derived sense—to elect—to choose. There were
several elders for each church as there had been several for each
synagogue, the model for the constitution of the early churches. They
were also called bishops (<span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p14.3"></span>επίσκοποι</span>). These with the deacons were
the only church officers. (<span id="vi.xxxi-p14.4"></span>[Phil. i.
1](../../../bib/kjv/phi001.htm#001)<span id="vi.xxxi-p14.5"></span>..md)
Their duty was to be leaders, teachers, and rulers in the churches. They
were at once pastors, teachers and rulers. Their functions were
coördinate. No one of them was above the others in any particular
church. Each church had several co-pastors, teachers or bishops.—G.B.S.

