class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p24.9"></span>νεμος</span> as an
interlinear correction arose the absurd reading <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p24.10"></span>πυρετός</span>.

<span id="fn_728"></span>[i:729](1110036.htm#fr_728.md) <span
id="vi.xxxi-p24.12"></span>

<span id="vi.xxxi-p25"></span> In the mod. text <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p25.1"></span>τὶ ποιοῦντες</span>; is
placed before <span class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p25.2"></span>Κονιν
επιβ</span> and <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p25.3"></span>σιγῶντες</span> is connected with <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p25.4"></span>τοὺς κύνας καλῶμεν</span>:
“by holding our peace let us call the dogs,” etc.

<span id="fn_729"></span>[i:730](1110036.htm#fr_729.md) <span
id="vi.xxxi-p25.5"></span>

<span id="vi.xxxi-p26"></span> In the original the sense is perplexed by
the negligent use of the demonstr. <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p26.1"></span>οὗτος</span> and <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p26.2"></span>ἐ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p26.3"></span>κεῖνος</span>, *supra* p. 42. The meaning is:
“B. (the second person mentioned) says to A. (suppose a <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p26.4"></span>πόρνη περιφανής</span>),
“You are so and so,” such being the fact: she retorts with a like
reproach, which is not true: whether is most damaged (<span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p26.5"></span>ὕ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p26.6"></span>βρισται</span>)? Not she,
for being what the other calls her she is just where she was before. The
disgrace is to him; and that, not from her words, for they do not fit:
but from his own indecent railing: so that he thinking to disgrace her
has more disgraced himself. He is more disgraced by calling the other
the thing that she is, than by being called by her the thing that he is
not.”

<span id="fn_730"></span>[i:731](1110036.htm#fr_730.md) <span
id="vi.xxxi-p26.10"></span>

<span id="vi.xxxi-p27"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.1"></span>ἀ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.2"></span>συνειδησίας ἄπιστον δόξαν λαβών</span>: which
being unintelligible, must be restored by replacing <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.3"></span>ἡ</span> before <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.4"></span>ασυν</span>. and before
<span class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.5"></span>ἀ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.6"></span>πιστου</span>(so mod. text
rightly for <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.7"></span>ἄ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.8"></span>πιστον</span>). “He gets the <span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.9"></span>δόζα</span> either of
<span class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.10"></span>ά</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="vi.xxxi-p27.11"></span>συνειδ</span>. in which
case he is a foul calumniator, or of an <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.12"></span>ἄ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.13"></span>πιστος</span>:” which latter in the way in
which it is put *supra* Hom. xiv. p. 193: “as regards himself, he has
shown all men that he is not to be trusted, as not knowing how to screen
his neighbor’s faults.”

<span id="fn_731"></span>[i:732](1110036.htm#fr_731.md) <span
id="vi.xxxi-p27.15"></span>

<span id="vi.xxxi-p28"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p28.1"></span>τῶν ἐπ᾽ ἀγορᾶς συρομένων</span>, not as Ben.
*eorum qui forum frequentant:* but, “one of those old hags, bawds, and
the like, whom for their crimes you may see dragged by the officers to
punishment, and screaming out their foul-mouthed railings.”

<span id="fn_732"></span>[i:733](1110036.htm#fr_732.md) <span
id="vi.xxxi-p28.4"></span>

<span id="vi.xxxi-p29"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p29.1"></span>ταῦτα ἐκ τῆς πόλεως τὰ συνέδρια</span>. So all
our <span class="c14"><span id="vi.xxxi-p29.2"></span>mss.</span>:
perhaps <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p29.3"></span>ταυτας</span>—<span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xxxi-p29.4"></span>τὰς συνηθειας</span>.

